{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476331"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:45:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:45:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13730"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13730"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.84,0.12,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6349"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103625"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6349"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86042"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44168"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103625"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old girl presents to her General Practice clinic with her mother with a two-day history of a non-blanching rash on her legs. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with normal vital signs. A purpuric rash is visible on her lower limbs (Image). Full blood count reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 128 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 6.5 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.5-13.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 3.0 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (1.5-8.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELymphocytes: 2.5 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (1.5-7.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 8 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer blood film is reviewed, and shows decreased platelets with normal appearing erythrocytes and neutrophils. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia","Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura","Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura","Meningococcal septicaemia","Disseminated intravascular coagulation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Eidiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterised by isolated thrombocytopenia in an otherwise well child. ITP is the most common cause of symptomatic thrombocytopenia in children. The diagnosis can only be made after excluding other causes of thrombocytopenia, and requires an otherwise normal full blood count (FBC) and film; this patient\u0027s FBC shows a very low platelet count with normal haemoglobin and white cell count, and her blood film is also consistent with an isolated cytopenia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute lymphoblastic leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can present with thrombocytopenia and purpura. However, there are usually other abnormalities on the full blood count, such as anaemia and neutropenia. The child may also have systemic symptoms like fever, fatigue, and bone pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHenoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura\u003C/strong\u003E is a small vessel vasculitis that can cause a purpuric rash. However, it is usually accompanied by abdominal pain, arthritis, and sometimes nephritis. The platelet count is typically normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningococcal septicaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can present with a purpuric rash, but the child would be systemically very unwell with high fever, tachycardia, and hypotension. The rash may progress to necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated intravascular coagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is a disorder of simultaneous clotting and bleeding that can cause thrombocytopenia and purpura. However, it always occurs secondary to another condition like sepsis, trauma, or malignancy. The coagulation profile (PT, aPTT, fibrinogen) would also be deranged, and one may see red cell fragmentation suggestive of microangiopathic haemolysis. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) is characterised by isolated thrombocytopenia in an otherwise well child.","The diagnosis of idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura is made after excluding other causes of thrombocytopenia."],"references":["James B Bussel, Immune thrombocytopenia (ITP) in children: Clinical features and diagnosis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/immune-thrombocytopenia-itp-in-children-clinical-features-and-diagnosis","Thomas A E, Baird S F, Anderson J. Purpuric and petechial rashes in adults and children: initial assessment. BMJ. 2016;352:i1285. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/352/bmj.i1285","Immune thrombocytopenia. The Royal College of Pathologists of Australia. Updated January 2024. Available from: https://www.rcpa.edu.au/Manuals/RCPA-Manual/Clinical-Presentations-and-Diagnoses/I/Immune-thrombocytopenia","Immune thrombocytopenic purpura. The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Updated March 2020. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/immune_thrombocytopenic_purpura/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86042"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13730"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20671"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20671"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1Nv9HGtyEpoAIRDVZjOXGswaXhjQza.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1Nv9HGtyEpoAIRDVZjOXGswaXhjQza.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":533}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86042"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-24T21:17:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-24T21:17:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6349"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103625"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","l